m.Payne shows that rather than argue for a particular way of life, postapocalyptic literature reveals what it would be like to inhabit that life. He considers the genre's appeal in our own historical moment, contending that this fiction is the pastoral of our time. Whereas the pastoralist and the maroon could escape to real-world hills and fashion their own versions of freedom, on a fully owned and occupied Earth, only an apocalyptic event can create a space where such freedoms are feasible once again.Flowers of Time looks at how fictional narratives set after the world's devastation represent new conditions and possibilities for life and humanity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aApocalypse in literature. 0aApocalyptic fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aDystopiasxHistory. 0aEnd of the world in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Science Fiction & Fantasy.2bisacsh  aApocalypse and Post-Politics.  aClaire Curtis.  aGilgamesh.  aHeather Hicks.  aHesiod.  aJohn Hay.  aMargaret Atwood.  aMary Manjikian.  aMary Shelley.  aPost-Apocalyptic Culture.  aPostapocalyptic Fantasies in Antebellum American Literature.  aPostapocalyptic Fiction and the Social Contract.  aTeresa Heffernan.  aTerminal Vision: The Literature of Last Things.  aThe Last Man.  aThe Post-Apocalyptic Novel in the Twenty-First Century.  aUrsula Le Guin.  aWarren Wagar.  aancient.  aapocalypse.  acatastrophe.  acivilization.  afreedom.  amaroon.  amemory.  amyth.  anature.  apastoral.  aphilosophical training.  aprimitive.  asurvival practice.  asurvival.  asurvivalist anthropology.  asurvivalist fiction.  athe apocalyptic cosmos.  azombie.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyt